                                                                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="14720201" author="srowen" created="Fri, 28 Aug 2015 16:36:09 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I think this was changed to allow 0 (could be misremembering this) so you can start with 0 executors and only request them once something needs to do work. However if you&apos;re saying executors never get requested, that&apos;s a problem of course.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14720222" author="tgraves" created="Fri, 28 Aug 2015 16:52:09 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Unless something else has changed 0 was allowed when you have dynamic allocation enabled.  Without that I don&apos;t know how you request executors after it has started for yarn cluster mode.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14720276" author="vanzin" created="Fri, 28 Aug 2015 17:23:49 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;You can call &lt;tt&gt;SparkContext::requestExecutors&lt;/tt&gt; even with dynamic allocation off, right? Still, I agree that it&apos;s a little weird to not at least print a nasty warning to the user in that case.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14728292" author="holdenk" created="Thu, 3 Sep 2015 00:30:59 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Looking at the code, it seems like the relevant logic is still there (L114). I&apos;ll dig into it a bit more.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14728312" author="holdenk" created="Thu, 3 Sep 2015 00:52:51 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;It seems that we aren&apos;t properly loading the number of executors when we are validating inside of ClientArguments.scala , I&apos;m not sure if this is worth fixing for 1.5.0 but I&apos;ll make a PR to fix this and we can decide.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14728328" author="apachespark" created="Thu, 3 Sep 2015 00:59:11 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;User &apos;holdenk&apos; has created a pull request for this issue:&lt;br/&gt;
